<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-127-242  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 127 242.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications News  Jan 1990 v27 n1 p30(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Guard your PBX. (security of telephone systems)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Thieves who steal private branch exchange (PBX) access codes cancause thousands of dollars in losses as they use the codes to makeexpensive overseas calls via computer.andP;  A simple computer programcan crack personal identification numbers (PINs) by guessingcommonly-used ones, such as installation dates or simple digits insequence.andP;  Hackers armed with valid PINs can get a dial tone froma PBX switchboard and call anywhere in the world.andP;  Stolen PINs arewidely sold on college campuses, military bases, and in theimmigrant community.andP;  Security measures include 'black box'devices that shut down lines for 30 minutes after a limited numberof incorrect access attempts; complex PINs; restricting codeaccess by time of day, area code, or number of calls per day; andphysically protecting remote maintenance ports.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     PBXAccess ControlsComputer CrimesComputer Hackers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>